## 🤖 **Day 23 of My 90 Days of Reinforcement Learning Journey**

### **Understanding Advantage Actor–Critic (A2C)**

Today, I explored **Advantage Actor–Critic (A2C)** — an important improvement over the basic Actor–Critic method.

A2C introduces the **advantage function**, which helps the agent understand *how much better an action is compared to the average*.
This reduces variance and stabilizes learning.

---

### 🧠 **Key Concepts**

🔹 **Advantage Function**
[
A(s, a) = Q(s, a) - V(s)
]
This tells the agent:
*“Was this action better or worse than what I usually do in this state?”*

🔹 **Actor Update**
[
\theta \leftarrow \theta + \alpha A_t \nabla_\theta \log \pi_\theta(a_t|s_t)
]

🔹 **Critic Update**
[
\phi \leftarrow \phi + \beta (R_t + \gamma V_\phi(s_{t+1}) - V_\phi(s_t))
]

---

### 💡 **Why A2C Matters**

* More stable than REINFORCE
* Lower variance than vanilla Actor–Critic
* Helps agents take more informed steps toward optimal policies
* Used as a foundation for more powerful algorithms like **A3C** and **PPO**

